Hey Seaders, thanks for your Issue!

---

### Recommendation

My recommendation is to keep your two declaration files separate. This approach makes your content declarations more maintainable and flexible, especially if you plan to use the visual editor.

```ts
import { type DeclarationContent } from 'intlayer';

const overviewContent = {
  key: 'overview',
  content: {
    header: 'Do all this awesome stuff with ',
    subHeader: ['With ', " you'll be even more awesome!"],
  },
} satisfies DeclarationContent;

export default overviewContent;
```

```tsx
import { useIntlayer } from 'next-intlayer'; // or react-intlayer
import { type FC } from 'react';

export const YourComponent: FC = () => {
  const { brandName, brandNameShort } = useIntlayer('app');
  const { header, subHeader } = useIntlayer('overview');
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>
        {header}
        {brandName}
      </h1>
      <h2>
        {subHeader[0]}
        {brandNameShort}
        {subHeader[1]}
      </h2>
    </div>
  );
};
```

### Alternative: Importing One Content File into Another

If you'd like to use TypeScript declaration files, an alternative is to import one content file into the other.

Here’s an example:

```ts
import { type DeclarationContent } from 'intlayer';
import appContent from './app.content';

const overviewContent = {
  key: 'overview',
  content: {
    header: `Do all this awesome stuff with ${appContent.content.brandName}`,
    subHeader: `With ${appContent.content.brandNameShort}, you'll be even more awesome!`,
  },
} satisfies DeclarationContent;

export default overviewContent;
```

It will works properly, but the limitation of this approach is its compatibility with the visual editor for your `overviewContent` content declaration file. The editor will interpret `Do all this awesome stuff with Other Detail: Company Name` as a single string fully declared in your `overviewContent` declaration file. The visual editor does not interpret nested declaration for now.

### Alternative: Using Component Logic

Another option is to call your content as a string using `.value` and replace placeholders with JavaScript's `replace` function.

```tsx
import { useIntlayer } from 'next-intlayer'; // or react-intlayer
import { type FC } from 'react';

export const YourComponent: FC = () => {
  const { brandName, brandNameShort } = useIntlayer('app');
  const { header, subHeader } = useIntlayer('overview');

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{header.value.replace('%%{app.brandName}%%', brandName.value)}</h1>
      <h2>
        {subHeader.value.replace(
          '%%{app.brandNameShort}%%',
          brandNameShort.value
        )}
      </h2>
    </div>
  );
};
```

However, this approach sacrifices the benefits of the `IntlayerNode` (type returned by objects like `brandName`, `brandNameShort`, `header`, or `subHeader`). These types enable features such as displaying the content selector within the visual editor.

### Content Nesting

I know that **i18next** offers a similar feature called [`nesting`](https://www.i18next.com/translation-function/nesting). Would this be a feature you'd like to see in Intlayer? If so, and if there’s enough interest from others, let me know. I’d be happy to add it to the roadmap.

---

### Updated Visual Editor Documentation

Regarding the visual editor: A new documentation has been released since Intlayer v4. The previous visual editor have been slitted into two tools :
- [Intlayer visual editor (for locale declaration files)](https://intlayer.org/doc/concept/editor)
- [Intlayer CMS (for distant dictionaries)](https://intlayer.org/doc/concept/cms)

Because of a big refactor regarding the approach, the visual editor will be released in the coming days with version 4.1.0. Meanwhile, we are still working on improvements related to the CMS, which will be fully available next weeks.

